              <span id="reviewTextContainer320213067" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer272086111756773532"><i>“Part of him wanted to weep... but his purpose was rigid within him. He felt he could not bend to gentleness without breaking.”</i><br/><br/>And part of me wanting to dive out a window. This was one of the least satisfying, uninspired and ponderous series Ive had the misfortune and stubbornness to slog through. Anti -hero&apos;s should be written in a way that the reader develops some shred of empathy or understanding for, otherwise you&apos;re left with a story centered around a character that you don&apos;t give a damn ab</span>
  <span id="freeText272086111756773532" style="display:none"><i>“Part of him wanted to weep... but his purpose was rigid within him. He felt he could not bend to gentleness without breaking.”</i><br /><br />And part of me wanting to dive out a window. This was one of the least satisfying, uninspired and ponderous series Ive had the misfortune and stubbornness to slog through. Anti -hero's should be written in a way that the reader develops some shred of empathy or understanding for, otherwise you're left with a story centered around a character that you don't give a damn about. Thomas Covenant is a selfish and bitter character who's sole redeeming quality is that the reader be expected to pity him. This story was depressing, bland and forgettable.</span>
