    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1055002372" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1055002372" />
    <a title="Jack" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/34984449-jack"><img alt="Jack" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1440596207p2/34984449.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1055002372?book_show_action=true">Sep 14, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jack" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jack" href="/user/show/34984449-jack">Jack</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/34984449-jack?shelf=fantasy-sci-fi">fantasy-sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1055002372" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9920171084762862274">Is without doubt my favourite series of books and this is where it all began. It was my brother who first recommended the book to me and insisted that I read it straight away. Is the only book where as I was reading it I felt like the boy, Bastian in &apos;The Never ending Story&apos;. From the first to the last page I was in The Land. Without waffling on about how amazing Donaldson is as a writer and how criminally underrated his books are, I will share my view on the positives and negatives(I even like </span>
  <span id="freeText9920171084762862274" style="display:none">Is without doubt my favourite series of books and this is where it all began. It was my brother who first recommended the book to me and insisted that I read it straight away. Is the only book where as I was reading it I felt like the boy, Bastian in 'The Never ending Story'. From the first to the last page I was in The Land. Without waffling on about how amazing Donaldson is as a writer and how criminally underrated his books are, I will share my view on the positives and negatives(I even like the negatives) of this omnibus of books. Firstly;<br /><br /><br /><br />Positives<br />1) Strong world-building. Manages to blend fantastical ideas that seem plausible and unified in the world.<br /><br />2) Gripping story. Feels truly heavy in the weight of some of the consequences throughout the book. Many twists in the plot that I didn't see coming. <br /><br />3) Memorable and interesting characters that don't just feel like templates that blur into each other. <br /><br />4) Doesn't stray into adolescent tendencies like many fantasy authors are guilty of. Also has plenty of subliminal sub-texts that enriched the depth of the book. Have recommended this book to non-fantasy readers who have enjoyed it.<br /><br />Negatives<br />1) As is often mentioned Donaldson can go on and on with internal monologue, sometimes to the detriment of the pacing of the book.<br /><br />2) Since this is really three books, the book looks like a tome. Not something that is unfamiliar however to the seasoned epic fantasy reader.<br /><br />3) The main character 'Thomas Covenant' is like Marmite, as you have probably heard. Could have been played by Charlton Heston/Willem Defoe in a film version I always felt.<br /><br />4) Don't read this book if you like humour in your writing. Is on the serious, end of the universe kinda vibe.<br /><br />Finally, I cannot recommend this book and the following books enough. Is a shame that people feel the need to compare Donaldson to Tolkien so much because of the use of a ring. I personally think that he surpasses Tolkien with this series of books. If you are a fan of epic fantasy you must read this essential book. Oh how lucky you are.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9920171084762862274" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


